\f0\lang1055 16.What is hypothesis testing? What are hypothesis testing types? Please explain with examples.\par
\b0\fs22 A hypothesis is some kind of assumption and hypothesis testing is an inferential statistical technique to determine whether there is enough evidence in a data sample to infer that a certain condition holds true for the entire population. It is used to test the validity of a claim that is made about a population.\par
Take a random sample\par
Analyze the properties of the sample\par
Test whether or not the identified conclusions correctly represent the population\par
A hypothesis is generated about a population parameter.\par
Null Hypothesis: The null hypothesis is assumed to be true unless there is a strong evidence to the contrary. This claim that\rquote s on trial is called the null hypothesis.\par
Alternative Hypothesis: The alternative hypothesis is assumed to be true when the null hypothesis is proved false. The alternative hypothesis is the one you would believe if the null hypothesis is concluded to be untrue.\par
Framing Hypothesis:\par
\f2\u9679?\f3\lang1033  At the start of the experiment, the null hypothesis is assumed to be true.\par
\f2\u9679?\f3  If the data fails to support the null hypothesis, only then can we look to an alternative hypothesis\par
* If testing something assumed to be true, the null hypothesis can reflect the assumption:\par
Claim:  \ldblquote Our product has an average shipping weight of 3.5kg.\rdblquote\par
Null hypothesis: average weight = 3.5kg\par
Alternate hypothesis: average weight \f5\u8800?\f3  3.5kg\par
* If testing a claim we want to be true, but can\rquote t assume, we test its opposite:\par
Claim:  \ldblquote This prep course improves test scores.\rdblquote\par
Null hypothesis: old scores \f5\u8805?\f3  new scores\par
Alternate hypothesis: old scores < new scores\par
The null hypothesis should contain an equality (=, \f5\u8804?\f3  ,\f5\u8805?\f3 )\par
The alternate hypothesis should not have an equality (\f5\u8800?\f3 ,<,>)\par
\par
\b\f0\fs24\lang1055 17.What do you understand by Type I vs Type II error?\b0\fs22\par
Type I error is committed when the null hypothesis is true and we reject it, also known as a \lquote False Positive\rquote . Type II error is committed when the null hypothesis is false and we fail to reject it, also known as \lquote False Negative'.\par
\par
\b\fs24 18.What Is the Goal Of A/B Testing?\b0\fs22\par
It is a statistical hypothesis testing for randomized experiment with two variables A and B. The objective of A/B Testing is to detect any changes to the web page to maximize or increase the outcome of an interest. Example: Identify the click-through rate for a banner ad.\par
A/B testing is a fantastic method for figuring out the best online promotional and marketing strategies for business. It can be used to test everything from website copy to sales emails to search ads An example of this could be identifying the click-through rate for a banner ad.\par
